F. A. Praeger Publishers | 1965 | ISBN: N/A | English | 280 pages | PDF | 40.2 MB

The term "Romans" is used here in its widest sense to include not only the inhabitants of Rome and Roman Italy, but all those peoples of the ancient world who looked to Rome as the center of their government and culture, from the time of her first territorial acquisitions outside Italy until the end of the fifth century ad. The monuments Professor Toynbee discusses are therefore drawn from as wide a range of localities as possibleâ€”eastern and western as well as central.
